            AppRoutes = """["/dashboard"]""",
            Tags = """["dashboard","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Responsive Grid Breakpoints\n\nThe widget grid (gridstack) re-columns itself to the container width, not a fixed layout. `getResponsiveColumns(width)` picks the column count: width `< 768px` -> **1 column**, `< 1024px` -> **6 columns**, otherwise -> **12 columns**. A `ResizeObserver` on the grid container watches for width changes and calls `grid.column(newCols)` whenever the bucket changes, so resizing the window or collapsing the sidebar re-flows widgets live without a reload. Fixed grid params: `cellHeight: 60`, `margin: 4`, `float: false`, `animate: true`. Drag/resize are disabled on init (`disableDrag`/`disableResize: true`) and only enabled while edit mode (Customize) is on.\n\n## Layout Persistence & Refresh Cadence\n\n**Persistence model.** Your widget arrangement is stored under the user-preference key `dashboard:layout:v5` (the `v5` suffix versions the schema — a layout-model change bumps the key so stale layouts are ignored rather than mis-applied). The saved value is a `DashboardSavedLayout` = a list of `{ id, x, y, w, h }` per widget. `saveLayout()` writes it via `UserPreferencesService` (localStorage cache + debounced API PATCH) on every grid `change` event while editing, and on add/remove/reset; `loadSavedLayout()` restores positions after the DOM settles. Because it lives in user preferences, the layout follows you across sessions and devices. **Reset** clears `dashboard:layout:v5` and rebuilds from `WIDGET_REGISTRY` defaults. The Focus-mode flag is a separate preference, `dashboard:focusMode`, and is also mirrored in the URL as `?focus=true`.\n\n**Refresh cadence.** The first load uses the `LoadingService` global overlay (`loadData(true)`). After that, a background `interval` re-fetches the dashboard every **5 minutes** (`POLL_INTERVAL_MS = 5 * 60 * 1000`) via `loadData(false)` — silent, no overlay, so the page never flickers while you work. The subscription is scoped with `takeUntilDestroyed` so it stops when you leave the page. Ambient mode runs its own faster loop (see below), independent of this 5-minute poll.\n\n## Ambient Idle-Timeout Config\n\nAmbient mode can trigger automatically after a period of inactivity, and that timeout is user-configurable. The setting is stored under preference key `ambient:idleTimeoutMs` and **defaults to `0` (Off)** — auto-ambient is opt-in. Selectable values (`AMBIENT_IDLE_OPTIONS`): Off (`0`), 1 minute, 5 minutes, 15 minutes, 30 minutes, 1 hour. On init the dashboard reads the preference (falling back to `DEFAULT_AMBIENT_IDLE_MS = 0`) and calls `idleService.configure(timeoutMs)`. `IdleService` tracks `mousemove`, `mousedown`, `keydown`, `touchstart`, `scroll`, and `wheel`; when `timeoutMs <= 0` it never reports idle. When idle fires, the dashboard enters ambient mode **only if** it is not already ambient, not in Focus mode, and not editing the layout — so auto-ambient never interrupts deliberate work. Exiting ambient (Escape or any click) calls `idleService.reset()`. While ambient, the display refreshes its data every **60 seconds** and ticks the clock every **1 second**, independent of the standard 5-minute poll.\n\n## Action Items Trigger-Type Catalog\n\nThe Action Items widget renders system-generated `FollowUpTask` rows. Each task carries a `triggerType` that selects its Material icon via `TRIGGER_ICON_MAP` (unmapped types fall back to `task_alt`). The shipped trigger types and icons:\n\n- **QuoteExpiring** — `event_busy`\n- **LeadStale** — `person_off`\n- **InvoicePastDue** — `payments`\n- **DeliveryAtRisk** — `local_shipping`\n- **CostOverrun** — `attach_money`\n- **CertExpiring** — `badge`\n- **MaintenanceDue** — `build`\n- **QcFailure** — `error`\n- **ReturnReceived** — `assignment_return`\n- **SalesOrderConfirmed** — `shopping_cart`\n- **ShipReady** — `local_shipping`\n- **MaterialsReady** — `shopping_cart`\n- **ShipmentDelivered** — `local_shipping`\n\nTasks are sorted by due date ascending (null due dates sort last) and the widget shows at most **8** (`MAX_VISIBLE`); a 'more' affordance appears when the open count exceeds 8. Each row deep-links to its source record via `sourceEntityType`/source id (defaulting to `job` when the type is null), flags overdue due dates, and exposes a check button (`completeTask`) and a close button (`dismissTask`). Both actions call the `FollowUpTaskService` and optimistically remove the row. The widget loads only `Open` tasks; an empty state shows when none are outstanding.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded Dashboard training modules");
